    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I can help with that! The interest on your student loan is calculated based on the remaining principal balance. Each month, the interest is calculated by multiplying the remaining balance by the monthly interest rate (which is the annual interest rate divided by 12). This interest amount is then added to the remaining principal balance before your monthly payment is applied. So, even though you're making full payments, a portion of each payment goes towards paying off the interest, leaving less to reduce the principal. This is why it feels like the balance barely moves at first. As the principal decreases, the interest portion of your payment will also decrease, allowing more of your payment to go towards the principal. It's a bit like trying to dig a hole with a shovel while also trying to fill it with water; it takes time for the water (interest) to stop coming in before you can start digging deeper (reducing the principal).",
      "source": "target",
